  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial t}\n+\n\\mathcal{H}_T\n\\left(\nq,\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial q},t\n\\right)\n=\n0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $S(q,t)$ be the action function for a classical trajectory on the Trawinistic manifold.  \nThe canonical momentum is obtained from the action by:\n\n\\begin{equation}\np_q=\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial q}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe Hamiltonian density or Hamiltonian function in Trawinistic form is:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathcal{H}_T(q,p_q,t).\n\\end{equation}\n\nSubstituting $p_q=\\partial S/\\partial q$ into the Hamiltonian gives:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathcal{H}_T\n\\left(\nq,\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial q},t\n\\right).\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe Hamilton--Jacobi condition states that time evolution of the action cancels the Hamiltonian contribution:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial t}\n+\n\\mathcal{H}_T\n\\left(\nq,\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial q},t\n\\right)\n=\n0 .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThis equation translates Trawinistic Hamiltonian dynamics into an action-based evolution law.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
